View Data

  • Dependent y variable is Sale Price

  • Independent x variables are: Property Address, City, Zip Code, Date, property type, Cap Rate, Building Square footage, Floor Area Ratio, Class, Material, Condition, yeara built, Number of units, Number of tenants, longitude, and latitude.

  • Structure of Variables

  • Change to appropriate

Transform skewed data

-Price, Building Square foot, & Floor Area Ratio

-View new transformed price by categorical variables We see there is variance in ranges when looking at the cat. variables and price which may mean they have an impact.

-View transformed price by numerics also We see there is hopeful correlation between building square footage/Floor Area Ratio and price (but they may need to be looked at in the transformed form)

Compp07_17$Trans_Price <- log(Compp07_17$Sale_Price)
Compp07_17$Trans_BldgSF <- log(Compp07_17$`Bldg SF`)
Compp07_17$Trans_FAR <- log(Compp07_17$`Floor Area Ratio`)
Complete_07_17 <- Compp07_17 %>%

This is just some more info on the spread on the data, obviously multi-family is the large portion of our sample. And the uneven spread of the other categorical variables to property type may mean Building Class, Material, and Condition cannot be used in our analysis model.

First iteration of modeling

Including

MFmod <- step(lm(Trans_Price ~ Trans_FAR * Cap_Rate * Trans_BldgSF * `Number Of Units` * `Property Zip Code`, filter(Complete_07_17, PropertyType == 'Multi-Family')), direction = "both")
summary(MFmod)
plot(MFmod)

Retailmod <- step(lm(Trans_Price ~ Trans_BldgSF * Cap_Rate * Trans_FAR * `Property Zip Code`, filter(Complete_07_17, PropertyType == 'Retail')), direction = "both")
summary(Retailmod)
plot(Retailmod)

Officemod <- step(lm(Trans_Price ~ Trans_BldgSF * Cap_Rate * Trans_FAR * `Property Zip Code`, filter(Compp07_17, PropertyType == "Office")), direction = "both")
summary(Officemod)
plot(Officemod)
